castAddBody.text: I feel like I'm more generative when I do a lot of reading, and I don't really get that from podcasts (though I haven't tried audio books). I get something similar from programming--but the generator is more just like "I can't help but wish thing X existed to fix this shit."  Not the same idea quality. Lower synthesis.
I feel like I shouldn't be quite the same person here. Not really sure what that means yet though.

Last year I went to Stinson Beach for a year-delayed reception for a pandemic wedding. Guy who rented the venue accidentally double-booked and all he could figure out was... his place in Mill Valley. The redwoods infected my default process

Like, I think of myself as having been a few different people already? One was some kid who did god-knows what. Another was a poet and editor. Another is a programmer. But the odds that the next one will just end up sitting under the redwoods are a lot higher than I would've guessed in 2020.

I'm enough of an introverted lurker that it feels deeply weird to project myself into social space unless it's for a project. Now I'm at a party with no one I know. It'd be a waste to stand in the corner with a drink, but I don't really know what happens when I just step on the gas.

Happened to be listening to a recent (11/22/22) Ezra Klein podcast on reading, and from 18:50-20:05 he expresses how reading on a plane often gets him here (and expresses what the state is better than I did...). Screenshot of it in the transcript.  https://i.imgur.com/28TL0Y0.png

Seeing effort go into designed obsolescence annoys me about as much as seeing it go into ~attention-engineering. No clue how we align the incentives. Excuse IP infractions when the resulting product is more durable/repairable the infringed one while costing no more? :)

Talked w/ someone who asserted that they'd experienced ego death caused by having to re-do significant amounts of PhD work due to faculty churn. I was aware of the concept, but hadn't ever heard someone claim it beyond some drug stories. Have you experienced what you think of as (non-drug) ego death?
The ability to sort (by last cast date) and filter your follow list (follows-me) would make this pretty easy for the monkey :)

Struggling with same. If I use it the same as twitt/masto there's a gravity towards wanting to crosspost (or having to waste brain considering what goes where). Crossposting isn't inauthentic to my self, but it does feel like an inherently inauthentic way to engage with a community.
words... https://i.imgur.com/fcxT5Sp.png

Spotted an interesting use of passwordless telnet as a connection test in Heroku's docs. It's been so long since I've seen it *recommended* for anything :) https://i.imgur.com/db7G8Ts.png
These are lovely. The conceptual framing strikes me as a sort of reverse Sol LeWitt thing :)

Since I saw https://allenpike.com/2022/giving-a-shit this summer, I've thought about it in terms of "giving a shit as a service." I feel like it's easier to trust the handoff/delegation to someone you know gives a shit (even if they *aren't* "better" at the task yet) than it is to hand it off to an expert that doesn't?
I guess in turn that all handoffs are easier if your whole org is selecting for people who give a shit...

Anyone  interested in nix, shell, or markup+documentation? 

Debating whether to discuss any of the OSS work I've been doing the past few years.

Isn't the hard part still knowing exactly what you want or need? Won't the ~boss still want to delegate thinking that through?

This and the SQL example feel more like the latest version of the cybernetic implant hiding behind the "advanced googling" skill on someone's resume.

Fewer seats via peer productivity seems right. Was reading you the other way around (enabling people 1 node up the management chain to answer more questions themselves).

Wonder if we'll see union-member-only *.stackexchange equivalents in an attempt to control model inputs.

A friend commented on the math thing today, and it made me want to read chatgpt's surprises as interesting emergent behavior caused by leaning really hard in to some vaguely neural capability. 

A kind of savant. Roughly what we could be if we subtracted most of the person and turned a few bits up to 11111.

I don't pay much attention to crypto research, but I imagine the threat model is a bit different? DARPA has to keep political meddling out of the risk-taking ~safe space.

The friction bits apply to both, but the overhead probably does maintain trust--and risk appetites in crypto seem to be ~big?
Good distinction on big speculative risk vs ~big goals. <3
Lagrange points but for temperature + daylight hours? :)
Enjoying this paper about the language we use to describe what LLMs are doing (shared by @AnthonyBaker@mastodon.social) https://arxiv.org/pdf/2212.03551.pdf https://i.imgur.com/S9Fzoxh.png
https://i.imgur.com/tmVLIOr.png

I like it because it's a good nudge to consider to what extent or how frequently the mode *we* are operating in is just text prediction. To this end I think it's telling how easy it is for ChatGPT to pass our smell-test before we really start breaking down what the language means.

The sense in which it is ~writing seems to be well-matched for the sense in which we are ~understanding before we engage critical mode.

I see this in writing/editing, too. Even good technical editors can let a lot of shit slip by until they hit something that smells bad enough to knock them into critical mode.
Should make a bot that rewrites articles that mention Musk to use his fauxnouns

I wondered aloud a few days ago about how different the world would be if we had really big people that could still dangle an average adult by our ankles and tickle us at will. 

Seems like it'd be hard to take ourselves too seriously if there was a legitimate chance we'd get inverted and tickled in line to order food?

Might be retconning motive, but I think I did this to save time and improve my feed. I mostly ~lurk in read/reply mode, so I didn't find twitter much fun until I put effort into my follows.

I can of course find replacement WX/OSINT/climatology/etc. follows, but ~porting a fifth helped me get back to having fun.
Blinded from this truth by how annoyed I am that the cups, regardless of whether they supposedly contain coffee or hot chocolate, are almost always obviously empty.

I haven't watched (yet), but I enjoyed the book a lot in college. Probably not missing much if you've read enough postmodern novels to take the shine off of the common tropes. But I do recommend it and Catch 22 to anyone who hasn't.

Watched tonight. Of two minds. Actually fairly impressed with how well they translated it to the screen, but also didn't feel like it worked terribly well. 

Like trying to read Tarantino or something? Like there's a lot of formal self-awareness that is harder to ~read in a different media.
Mom got me one of those flying ball/orb toys. I'm sure I'll eventually break something with it, but the anticipation is a fair fraction of the fun.

Seen this kicking around but it feels pretty expected? I doubt there's a good way for mastodon to squint and claim lurkers are MAUs, but I imagine most of Twitter's MAUs are lurkers--yeah?

I need a term for that late-yak-shave feeling:

you've gotten ~used to persisting on incredibly small doses of accomplishment and suddenly multiple large parts are ready to slot into place with minimal additional effort.

After months/years of accomplishment drought, it's accomplishment monsoon.

Costs presumably wouldn't be prohibitive to ideologues of the sort who already donate to orgs and political candidates/parties to advance their agenda. Nor to state/corporate actors trying to shape the past/present.
I have a space heater with a little remote. But there's no holder on the space heater, so the remote lives in a junk drawer, probably. Without batteries, I hope.

This would double down on the risk LLMs are laundering misinfo, no?

I also expect avoiding liability is more complex than just paying someone with a pulse to thesaurus words. I think a jury would agree the work was copied if there's deep, undeniable structural similarity.
How would you react/triage if new users started reporting problems understanding docs while the tests pass or the LLM generates summaries that sound like understanding to core deva?

Yeah. I agree usability testing would be important. 

I guess I'm wondering aloud about the possibility that the LLM encourages documentation in conflict w/ what human readers need? (maybe moot if it's more important that codegen LLMs can read it...)
Like how SEO-optimal pages can be quite suboptimal for humans in some cases.
Minimum bar and good at reading bad docs capture it well. If I had to pick a direction, it's: overconfidence that concepts are clear just because the LLM uses the right jargon.
Refuse to make one on principle. Also, schadenfreude at all of the spearphishing attempts aimed at people who do :)

Tbh finding the strong crypto founder effect here a but... Something. I don't get the sense that there's much audience for my main posting interests here so I lurk even harder than elsewhere.

My intuition is that the market for non-pulpy/-airport fiction is minimal and skews ~writerly (which as an MFA in writing I suspect is a vicious cycle) with thinning opportunity for success rockets. 

A big YA book (or series) can still crush it in the market, so there are concordant network effects.

I haven't needed to do too much secrets stuff, but Nix can help standardize the environment. Most of our secret cases so far have been things that we can readily generate/rotate or mirror from prod via CLI. I think most people are using agenix or sops-nix for this bit.

If you don't have a resident Nix-er, I'd explore via higher-level projects focused on this case: floxdev.com, devenv.sh,  github.com/nickel-lang/organist, jetpack.io/devbox/. Unfortunately haven't used these yet so I can't narrow. The organist README briefly compares all of these.
